Hi,
We have been trying to implement radiative cooling on the interface between two different materials, with different material properties, that are in the same block.
This is so that elements can change variables without having to move the element between blocks, which is the major contributor to the run time.
For our application, we have chosen to distinguish between the two materials using an additional 'switch' variable which is either 1 or 0 on the nodes rather than using two blocks.
We also change the material properties as a function of their position.
Since we no longer have a sideset to apply a BC to, we wanted to see if it was possible to apply an equivalent radiative heat flux kernel that radiates heat from nodes that are approximately at the materials interface.
To do this, we have implemented the following kernel based on the RadiativeHeatFluxBase BC from the Heat Conduction module. This only returns a non zero residual contribution if the switch value is between the threshold values given; in this case those thresholds are 0.1 and 0.9.
#pragma once

#include "RadiationCooling2.h"

#include "Function.h"

#include "MathUtils.h"

registerMooseObject("MyApp", RadiationCooling2);

InputParameters
RadiationCooling2::validParams()
{
   InputParameters params = ADKernelValue::validParams();
   params.addClassDescription(
       "Apply radiative cooling to the boundary of phi (phi = 0.5). This acts as a heat sink so takes energy out of the model.");
   params.addRequiredCoupledVar("switch", "switch value");
   params.addParam<Real>("thresh", 0.1, "Threshold for the gradient value");
   // params.addRequiredCoupledVar("phi", "The level set variable");
   params.addParam<Real>("ambient_temperature", 300, "The ambient temperature");
   // params.addRequiredParam<Real>("sigma", "The standard deviation of the Gaussian around the interface");
   params.addParam<Real>("factor", 1.0, "Scaling coefficient to multiply the heat sink by");
   params.addParam<MaterialPropertyName>("emissivity", "emissivity", "The name of the emissivity material.");
   return params;
}

RadiationCooling2::RadiationCooling2(const InputParameters & parameters)
 : ADKernelValue(parameters),
 _switch(adCoupledValue("switch")),
 _thresh(getParam<Real>("thresh")),
 _T0(getParam<Real>("ambient_temperature")),
 _emissivity(getADMaterialProperty<Real>("emissivity")),
 _factor(getParam<Real>("factor"))
{
}

ADReal
RadiationCooling2::precomputeQpResidual()
{
   if((_switch[_qp] > _thresh) && (_switch[_qp] < (1-_thresh))){  // new

       ADReal heatFlux = 5.670367e-14 * std::max(std::pow(_u[_qp], 4) - std::pow(_T0, 4), 0.0); // TempDiff always greater than 0
     return  _factor * _emissivity[_qp] * heatFlux;
   }
   else{

       return 0;
   }
}
We have tried this on a simple 2D test case consisting of a metal square (switch=1) within a larger air square (switch=0). We also created an equivalent metal square with a FunctionRadiativeBC on the external boundary and compared the temperatures of both the models over time.
From our tests we have found that:
The cooling needs to be multiplied by a 1/element length. This has been tested with different resolutions and has been shown to hold.
All of these results are still out by a factor of ~1.2, when testing with squares of different resolutions in 2D, and also cubes in 3D, as seen below.

However, when trying to validate with a circle instead, the factor of 1.2 is not correct.
My questions:
Is this a feasible approach to take?
Do you have any ideas where the factors may have come from?
Is there a better way to do it?
Thanks for your time

